{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958050201/0254.xml":{"full_text":"Baffle Shaping in Congress\nParties Split Over\nAction on Recession\nThe stage was set for a major anti-recession battle in\nCongress as House Democrats drove to pass a sweeping\nemergency jobjess-pay program and Pres Eisenhower\nlaunched Republicans on a determined effort to whittle\nit down.\nI\nThe prospect for tax cuts\nremained uncertain as Demo\ncrats hestitated and the Ad-i\nministration specifically refused;\nto make a decision one way or\nanother. A sensational Rockefel-|\nler Brothers Fund report, warn\ning the White House to stop;\ndragging its feet on tax reduc\ntion and public works, made no\nnoticeable impact on the Presi\ndent.\nI\nOn other anti recession pro\nposals the picture was almost i\nuniform\u20141 i b e r al Democrats\npushed while the Administra\ntion resisted or sought to re\nduce the Fulbright local public\nworks bill, the Douglas-Payne\ndistressed areas-bill, the farm\nprice and rivers-and -harbors\nbills already vetoed by the\nPresident but not yet consider\ned officially dead.\nSenate Democratic Leader\nLyndon Johnson (D-Tex called\nfor \"bold\" action while Com\nmerce Sec. Sinclair Weeks,\nspeaking for the Administration,\nexpressed the official GOP warn\ning against \"the ballyhoo of\nmanufactured gloom The eco\nnomic indicators continued\ndownward lower industrial\nproduction, bigger unemploy\nment insurance rolls, and a Com\nmerce Dept, report stating that\nthe percentage of consumers\u2019 in\ncome spent on durable goods had\nhit a 10-year low.\nKnowland Blocks Action\nin a side action, Republican\nFloor Leader William F. Know\nland (Calif.) checked a quick\ndecision on the Douglas-Ken\nnedy-Ives bill, designed to pro\ntect employe welfare and pen\nsion plans, by successfully de\nmanding a vote on his own ex\ntraneous proposals on so-called\nunion \u201cdemocracy\nEisenhower sent ap his\nwarning rocket on unemploy\nment compensation as Know\nland and House GOP Leader\n(Mass.)\nJoseph Martin\nemerged from their weekly\nWhite House conference\nspeaking of a \u201cmajor\u201d fight.\nKnowland underscored the\nintensity of the President's op\nposition to the Democratic\nsponsored measure, which\nwould pump $1.6 hillion to 4\nmillion Jobless workers, by\nwarning that the bill would\nrun into a White House veto.\nThe bill, observed Knowland,\n\u201cgoes much farther\u201d than the\nAdministration's own limited\nproposals.\nAs reported out by the House\nWays and Means Committee the\nmeasure would grant 16 weeks\nof emergency federal jobless pay\nregardless of whether or not un\nemployment workers were eli\ngible under their local state re\nstrictions.\nFederal Standards Rejected\nThe money would go outright\nfrom the federal government\nThe bill, which is closer to a pro\nposal by Ways and Means Chair\nman Wilbur Mills (D-Ark.) than\nto the Administration's recom\nmendations, would not adopt the\nAFL-CIO-backed proposal for\nbasic federal minimum standards\nfor all state jobless compensa\ntion systems\nThe Democratic measure is\n\u201cfar superior\" to the Eisenhower\nproposal but still is only a \u201cstop\ngap\u201d bill that fails to \u201crecognize\nthe need for minimum stand\nards,\" the AFL-CIO Industrial\nUnion Dept, said in a statement\nissued by Dir Albert White\nhouse.\nArea Redevelopment Advances\nThe Senate Banking Commit\ntee, i g n o r i n g an Eisenhower\nWeeks warning of Administra\ntion opposition, reported favor\nably the Douglas-Payne area-de\nvelopment bill to use $380 mil\nlion in federal funds to assist\ncommunities afflicted by acute\nand chronic unemployment\nWeeks said that Eisenhower\nopposed anything more than\n$50 million. Five Democrats\nand three Republicans voted\napproval of the $380 million,\nfour Republicans and three\nDemocrats voted against it.\nFrustrated on farm legislation\nand the rivers-and-harbors bill\nby the Eisenhower vetoes, John\nson moved to keep the legisla\ntion alive by asking the Agricul\nture and Public Works Commit\ntee, to conduct hearings on the\nveto messages, examine them\n\u201cword for word\u201d and see wheth\ner the President had correctly\nweighed the \u201cfacts.\u201d\nThe Rockefeller Brothers\nFund report, drafted by a 17\nmember panel of economists,\nbusinessmen and educators,\nsharply warned that swift short\nrange action to end the business\nslump is urgently needed to clear\nthe way for enormous potential\neconomic expansion.\nThe national economy can\ngrow by 5 percent a year, the\npanel headed by former Federal\nReserve Board Chairman Thom\nas B McCabe said. Such an ex\npansion alone, it stated, can sup\nport the huge defense structure\nrequired and establish the high\ner living standards demanded by\nthe people\nAsk Immediate Tax Cut\nLong-range expansion is im\npeded, however, by the immedi\nate recession and the need is for\nswift action including \u201caggres\nsive\u201d selling and \u201cbetter values\u201d\n(meaning price cuts) by busi\nness, creation of a top-level na\ntional economic council and Fed\neral Reserve Board action to\nease credit, the report declared.\nThe government, in turn,\nshould move for an \u201cimmediate\u201d\ntax cut, more and faster public\nworks and emergency federal\nunemployment compensation\nThe report failed to give a\nfigure for total tax reduction,\nbut the panel members gen\nerally agreed that about $S\nbillion in tax relief was de\nsireable. Reduction by that\namount has been recently en\ndorsed by former Pres. Harry\nTruman and by Arthur F.\nBurns, Eisenhower\u2019s former\nCouncil of Economic Advisers\nchairman.\nSen.\nMike\nMansfield\n(D\nMont) became the first leading\ncongressional Democrat\u2014he is\nSenate assistant majority leader\n\u2014to sponsor a tax-cut measure.\nHe filed a bill to abolish most\nincome- tax exemptions from\nexcise levies and raise personal\n$000 to $800\nAny bill must be originated,\nhowever, in the House, and the\nDemocratic leaders are still hon\noring a \u201cgentlemen\u2019s agreement\u201d\nwith Treasury Sec. Robert B.\nAnderson to give advance notice\nbefore moving\n1\nCleveland 1\n4 FT AI\nAFL, CIO\nIn Merger\nCleveland\u2014Not a single\n_, D*\nvote was cast here\nCleveland Federation o _\nand the Cleveland Industrial\nion Council,\n\"no'\nwhen the\nof Labor\nUn\nsessions, voted to end\nyear-old\nmeeting in separate\ntheir 21\nseparation and merge\nintothe.Ci eve 1a n d AFL-CIO\nFederation of Labor w\ndelegates from 200 local unions\nend their first meeting in Cleve\nland Public Auditorium, the gen.\nWhen 500\neral feeling was one of satista\nIlion that the local house\n|bor is united once more.\nCongratulati\u2014\nof la\nsretulations on the\nsamation, first of the bij-ctty\nmergers in the nation,\n(from AFL-CIO Pres\ni Meany and Pres.\ncame\niIrany and Pres. WilHam\u00b0Pol\nI lock of the Textile Workers Un\n*on among others. Pres. Michael\nLyden of the Ohio State\nton of Labor installed\nficers\ne\nUn\nFedera\nthe of\nThe 21-man\nhas 11 CFL\nexecutive board\nrepresentatives\nand 10 from the CIUC.\nofficers\nTop\nare Pat J. O\u2019Malley.\nER\u2018 _\n\u25a0n Auto Worker,\npres de nt an Ironworker,\nmna _ T\nThomas E. McDonald,\nPaid board chairman; 2\nas un\nber of the Staze Hands, mem\nWIL\nI ex\nHam Finegan, as full-time\neeutive secretary, and his\npaid assistant\nsecretary.\nAffiliated local\nas\nrecording\n_ unions will\nPay a per capita tax of 5\nper member per month\nmembership. Affiliated\nare entitled to\nthe first 100 members or major\nfraction; one delegate for\nadditional 100 members\njor fraction up to 500; and\ndelegate for every 500 ad\u201citional\nmembers or major fraction.\nCommittees from\nCIUC worked\ncents\non full\nunions\none delegate for\neach\nor ma\none\nto work out\nmore than a\nCFL and\nyear\nmerger terms. There\nwere no serious obstacles, and no\nstubborn holdouts.\nNegotiators\nwere determined to get an\nagreement that would work, and\nwould be acceptable to all\nU68.\npar\nCFL offices will be\nfrom Carpenters Hall\nthey have been for 40 years\nor more. CIUC offices will b\u2019\nmoved from CIO Hall, and the\nbuilding put up for sale at an\nclmated Proceeds\nfiat\n225S!\u201cr\"m.pve!dlng modern\nmoved\nwhere\nurged to\nbe\nThe Curtis E. Etchen Co.\nAdvertising Specialties\nGifts. imports, Pens, Pencils,\nBadges, All Union Made.\nCourtesy discounts to Unions.\n208 Spitier Bldg. CH 1-6735\nJ. F. ANDERSON\nCOMPANY, INC.\nResidential and Commercial\nConstruction\nCOMPLETE REMODELING AND\nMODERNIZATION SERVICE\n2852\nSouth\nWA 3414\n\"Even on holiday do you have to get up and\nlisten to 'EYE OPENER'?\"\nI\nI\nLISTEN to EYE OPENER with GUY NUNN\nFeaturing MUSIC NEWS WEATHER SPORTS\nL\nprasontod a pubhe by the UAW\n.1\n\u2022e\ni \u201cres\nsadn -4\nt\n\n\u201cGREATEST EXHIBITION of anti-labor propaganda ever pro\nduced\u201d is now being sent to congressmen by employer groups, Rep.\nElmer J. Holland (D-Pa.), charges as he points to some of the ex\namples reaching his office in recent weeks. Holland charged that\n\u201ca chain letter writing system has been set up in every Congress\nman\u2019s district\u201d as part of \u201ca well-planned plot to destroy the gains\nof labor and to stop labor\u2019s progress\u201d through enactment of legisla\ntion to \u201cregulate\u201d unions and curb their \u201cabuses.\u201d\nMeany Raps Brazen I\nLie In 6 Work Laws\nSan Bernardino, Calif. The\n\u201chigh-powered brazen lie,\u201d an\noft-used technique in attempts\nto destroy the trade union move\nment, is the major weapon em\nployed by proponents of \u201cright\nto-work\u201d laws, AFL-CIO Pres.\nGeorge Meany charged here.\nThey are employing the lie\ntechnique by broadcasting\nthroughout the nation that a law\nto prohibit the union shop will\nguarantee to everyone \u201cthe right\nto work,\u201d Meanv said.\n\u201cThe shoddy proposition\nmislabeled \u2018the right to work\u2019\nconveys neither rights nor\nwork,\u201d the AFL-CIO president\nasserted. \u201cIt will not create\none new job. It will not re\nstore one worker now unem\nployed to a payroll. It will not\nsave the job of a single per\nson who now faces impending\nlayoff.\u201d\nWhat it will do, he told a large\naudience at the annual Orange\nFestival here, is to weaken un\nions and bring about \u201clower\nwages and living standards, low\ner purchasing power, shrunken\nmarkets, depressed communities\nand fewer job and profit op\nportunities.\u201d\n\u2018No Place in California*\nNoting the current campaign\nto enact a \u201cright-to-work\u201d law\nin California via the referendum\nroute, Meany declared that the\nstandards and practices of Missi\nssippi a right-to-work law\nstate\u2014have no place in Cali\nfornia.\nHe noted also that there are\n\u201ccertain ambitious politicians\nwho apparently think that the\npublic has now been condi\ntioned to embrace an anti-la\nbor platform as a substitute\nfor a constructive program\nand that the wings of a lie\nafford a suitable vehicle to\nride to political preferment.\u201d\nMeany, setting the background\nfor\nthe current\nanti-labor drive\nin the state, pointed out that la\nbor's awareness of the danger\nof the lie technique comes from\n\u201cbitter firsthand experience\u201d in\nbattles over child labor, the\nconspiracy doctrine, the open\nshop drives of past years, the\n\u201cAmerican Plan\u201d and the \"la\nbor monopoly bugaboo.\u201d\nHe detailed the economic con\nditions in the \u201cright-to-work\u201d\nlaw states, noting the high rate\nof unemployment and adding:\n\u201cThe rest of the citizens of\nthose states that have chosen\nto follow this treacherous path\nhave also lost a great deal.\nWhen they swallowed the lie\nthat strong trade unionism im\npairs liberty and discourages\nenterprise and that repressive\nanti-labor legislation is neces\nsary to the attraction of in\ndustry or the promotion of the\neconomic development of a\nstate, they betrayed not only\nlabor but themselves as well.\u201d\nThroughout the world, Meany\nsaid, where the trade union\nmovement is weakest and least\neffective, the chances are that\nin those countries there are also\nversions of \u201cright-to-work\u201d laws\nthat stymie economic progress.\nAs to the question of freedom,\nthe AFL-CIO president declared\nthe worker does not \u201cbegin to\nrealize his full measure of free\ndom until he joins a union. The\nalternative to trade unionism is\nnot liberty but the tyranny of\nthe company boss.\u201d\nBusiness itself, he added, is a\nvictim of the \u201cright-to-work\u201d\ncampaign with businessmen\nbeing exploited by \u201cprofessional\nhucksters and cynical oppor\ntunists who use these campaigns\nas a sure-fire means of tapping\nthe corporation till.\u201d\n20 TO 50% DISCOUNTS\nDiamonds\u2014Watches\nTrophies\u2014Gifts\u2014Appliances\nC. K. MERRILL CO.\n428 Superior\nCH 8-6623\nMort Edgington, Mgr.\nStandard Printing Go.\nBOOK JOB PRINTING\nWedding Announcements, Etc.\n520 Jackson CH 3-1705\nVisit The \u201c1 lth Frame\u201d\nRoom At\nCivic Cantor Grill\nand Cocktail Lounge\nLunches Dinners and Sandwiches\n445 Superior At Jackson\nAT&T Probe\nMay Reveal\nNew Mess\npartment\nAmerican\nA little publicized investiga\ntion by the House Anti-trust\nCommittee into a consent decree\nentered into by the Justice Ds\nwith the mammoth\nTelephone and Tele\ngraph Company may reveal a\nmess in Washington that rivals\ncurrent scandal in the\nCommunications Commis\nthe\neral\nsion. (See the Telephone Talk\nshop column).\nBack in 1949, the Department\nof Justice filed an anti-trust ac\ntion against the huge telephone\nmonopoly which, it said, oper\nclosed market in tele\ntion\na ted a\nphone equipment.\nAT&T is primarily a holding\ncompany .although it also oper\nates a Long Lines Department\nwhich provides most interstate\nlong distance service. It owns a\nmajority of the stock in all Bell\nSystem companies except me\nSouthern New England and Cin\ncinnati and Suburban Telephone\ntrie\nWestern\nCompanies.\nAT&T also owns 99 percent\nof the stock of the Western Elec\nCompany. It, together with\nElectric, owns the Bell\nTelephone Laboratories which,\nin turn, owns or\u2019controls impor\ntant communications and non\ncommunications patents.\nWestern Electric is the manu\nfacturer, supplier and installer\nof virtually all Bell System\nequipment, from the big dial ex\nchanges down to the mechanical\npencils supplied to telephone\noperators. It operates in a closed\nmarket and its prices are set\nlargely by agreement with Bell.\nIts operations affect telephone\nrates almost as directly as those\nof the Bell operating companies.\nIt has always been a highly pro\nfitable operation.\nIn entering its suit against the\nAT&T in 1949, the Justice De\npartment sought a bill of di\nvorcement of Western Electric\nfrom the Bell System. This\nwould have caused the telephone\nmonopoly to purchase supplies\nin the open market.\nIn January of 1956, the Just\nice Department dropped its anti\ntrust action. In return, the AT&T\nagreed to free certain patents\nand to permit manufacturers to\nuse other patents under license.\nThis decree, according to Em\nanuel Celler (D-N. Y.), chair\nman of the House Committee,\n\u201callows the Western Electric\nAmerican Telephone and Tele\ngraph relationship to continue\nvirtually undisturbed.\u201d\nThe investigation has brought\ninto the open details of an intra\noffice memo of T. Brooke Price,\nformer AT&T general counsel.\nThis memo described the details\nof a lengthy conversation be\nthe company lawyer and\nformer Attorney General\nBrownell at the latter\u2019s home in\nWhite Sulphur Springs, W. Va.,\ntween\nin June of 1953.\nBrownell, according to Price,\nwas seeking a way to get rid of\nthe case by finding practices\n\u201cthat we might agree to have\nenjoined with no real injury to\nour business.\u201d\nIn testimony before the House\nCommittee, Price declared that\nhe felt that Brownell was \u201cjust\ngiving us a friendly little tip.\nr\nRegistration Shown\nBy ACWA Survey\nA pilot project under\ntaken by the Clothing\nWorker* education depart\nment has disclosed that only\n20 to 30 per cent\u2014varying\nfrom shop to shop of\nACWA members in seven\nMaryland counties and one\nin Delaware had registered\nto vote.\nThe survey covered mem\nbers served by the union\u2019s\nEastern Shore Joint Board.\nIt was followed by a step\nped-up campaign for a huge\nturnout on April 15, the\nregistration date in Mary\nland, with\na registration\ncommittee set up in each\nshop. The area was select\ned because it is typical of\nsome others where the\nACWA has members\u2014shops\nin small communities with\nthe members often living in\nother sections.\nI\n40 199989\n(Geru\nBAD NEWS CONTINUES\nOn employment, wage, sales fronts: More and more\nworkers are losing their jobs, and there\u2019s nothing at present\nto give them much hope that they will get them back any\ntime soon.\n3W1I\u00ab\nThat\u2019s the long and short\nof the latest economic news.\nIn the week April 5, the latest\ndate for which figures are avail\nable, the number of persons\nclaiming unemployment com\npensation for the first time in\ncreased sharply. A record rate\n(7.9 per cent) of working peo\nple who are covered by jobless\ninsurance were collecting bene\nfits in the week ending March\n29. The total was upwards of\u2019\n3,300,000.\nI\nThe rate remained high de\nspite the fact that many unem-l\nployed working men and wom-|\nen have exhausted their unem-;\nployment insurance. The Depart\nment of Labor estimated that\n189,000 of the unemployed had\nreceived all benefits due them\nby the end of March, making a\ntotal of 481,000 since the first of\nthe year. Experts assume that\nexhaustions are still climbing at\nthe same rate or faster, and have,\ngone beyond the 500,000 mark!\nI\nby now.\nThe Commerce Department\nreported that wages and salaries\nfell again in March, and the re\ntail sales declined by 1 per cent.\nAnd the Federal Reserve Board\nsaid that industrial production\ndropped during March to the\nlowest point since the 1953-54\nrecession.\nI\nMeantime, the Big Three auto\nmakers reported sales of new\ncars during the first three\nmonths of the year were sharply\nbelow those during the first\nquarter of 1957. Chrysler Cor\nporation\u2019s new car sales were\ndown 45 per cent; Ford's 36 per 1\ncent; and General Motors\u2019, 18\nper cent.\nSTEEL PRODUCTION SLIPS:\nSteel production has dropped to\nits lowest point of the recession,\nSteel Magazine reports. Produc-j\ntion last week fell to only 48\nper cent of capacity. Production\nfor the whole year has averaged\nonly about one-half of capacity.\nMeanwhile, Iron Age magazine\nsaid that the automobile industry\nhas told steel manufacturers that\nit will be buying only limited\namounts of steel for the remain\nder of the 1958 model year. The\nnational metalworking weekly\nsaid that this means steel com\npanies can expect little help e\nfrom Detroit in pulling out of\nthe slump before August or Sep\ntember when orders will be giv\nen for steel to be used in 1959\nmodel cars. Of course, how large\nthose orders will be depends en\ntirely on the state of business.\nSHOULD THE PRESS WITH\nHOLD Bad News? \u201cWould the\neconomy brighten up if the\nnewspapers minimized all the\nbad economic news and blew up\nall the good\u2019 Of course not.\n\u201cThe results might be far more\nharmful; for once newspaper\nreaders sensed a deliberate ef\nfort to withhold or underplay\nbad news, they would lose con\nfidence in all press reports, good\nor bad, and might, indeed, be\ngin to imagine that the situa\ntion was far worse than it really\nwas.\u201d\u2014Greensboro (N. C.) Daily\nNews.\nTHE LAW AND THE PRESI\nDENT: \u201cIt is the responsibility\nof the Government to assure\nmaximum employment; produc\ntion and purchasing power.\u201d\u2014\nEmployment Act of 1946.\n\u201cThe Government should not\nbe the most important factor to\ndefeat a recession.\u201d\u2014President\nEisenhower, 1958.\nIKE SAYS HUNGER STATE\nPROBLEM: From Washington\nPost and Times Herald report\nof President Eisenhower\u2019s news\nconference of March 26: \u201cA re\nporter asked him if there wasn\u2019t\nsome way that surplus good held\nby the Government could be\ngiven to hungry Americans. He C\nsaid he agreed that something\nshould be done for people who\nare hungry, but not that it be\ndone from Washington.\u201d\nFrom same paper, same day:\n\"Leaksville, N. S., March 26\u2014A\n26-year-old unemployed man.\nwho apparently had no money\nto feed his family, put a bullet\nthrough his heart yesterday\nshortly after police arrested him\nfor trying to steal $3 worth of\nfood .Police had picked him\nup after he tried to get food for\nhis wife and two small daugh\nters.\u201d\nCROSSWORD PUZZLE\nLAST wan\nANSWER\nKOMU (d(9\nACROSS\n1. Drawing\nroom\nCapital\n(Bur.)\n11. Before\n(nout.)\n12. Fat\n13. An outfit\n14. Rough\nstone\n15.Constitu.\ntional\nIf Cota (Jap.)\nS. Compass\npoint\n(abbr.)\n6 Small bag\n1. Warp-yara\n8. Lee\u2019s men\n28. Girl\u2019s\nname\n28. Tibetan\npriest\n30. Caliber\n32. Blends\nSmall island 33. Arabian\n10. Observed\n14 Staple food\n(Chin.)\n16. Pleasing\n19. Competition\nM. ComW.\nlaticn\ngar\nments\n34. Vend\n35. Ex\n18. Wan re row 21. Pack\n20. Counsel\n23. Unit of\nmeter\n27. Lift\n22. Contend\n24. Sphere\n25, River (Sp.)\n000\n\"EmMPr\nHiV[Ir3 -JUNI:\nHiEOh 3373\n.It\n\u201c06 32124\n-iEU\nVOUGE u\"Gud\nHnQHaw OJHEH\nna\ni\nHEQE Dinu\nEVGAE Hu?\nqn3( aAUildat\nHESS HG\nchange\npremium\n87. Heathen\nimage\n88. Leather\nflask\nfanc. Gr.)\nP-278\n89. Haunt\n41. Un.\ndivid.\ned\n44. Measure\n(Chin)\nf\n28. Ghastly pale\n28. Incite\n30. Explorer\n4\n2\nT\nS\n7\ns\n9\nO\n(Sp.)\n81. Mouthlike\nopening\n28. King of\nJudah\n38. Speech\n40. Be off!\n42. Not\nworking\n43. Straighten\n(var.)\n44. Circles\n45. Astringent\nfruits\n06. Shore recess\nL\n2.\n8.\n4.\nT\n13\nW\n7\n17\nf)\n37\n29\n45\nis\n25\n30\n3\n31\n36\n2\n28\n37\n38\n39\nGRANDMA\nALBERT/)\nOH, ALBERT\n\nSHUCKS I WAS HOPIN\u2019 I COULD\nHIRE HIM V OO GET TH' ICC\nCRAM AH\u2019 CAKI FOR MY PARTY\nBy Charles Kuhn\nLL? DID 1 HEAR\nMXcCREAM\u2014\nCREAM\nDID YOU\nYOU SAY\nAN'\nJITTEA\n\nO\nI\nX 9 y\nI^UGBY\n1?ID\u20acS\nA6AIH\nA\nAB\u2019t\nBy ARTHUB POINIER\nVIRGIL\nWOULD U a\nLIKE T COMG\nOVER ANO PLN\nTRAINS WITH\nME, VIReIT C\n&d! X\n_ SURE\nCWOULD\n(DANI\n_2\n(A M\n7\n\nMAN! DAMN\u2019S\nGCTT\u2019 BGGEST\nTRAN LMHOUT\nITOWI!\nAe! MOT WrH\nTAATTHINS=\nI WANT TO\nPLPH RSAL\nTRAINS\nREAL\nTO WHS\n\nif\n0\nf.\nBy Len Kleis\nC\nMUTT AND JEFF\nLOOK AT\nTHE COWARD?\nTHAT GUY! I IM GOING OVER\nHE STRUcK AND TELL HIM\nAWOMAN/D\n--y\u2014\nOFFL\n-===4\nT\nMDU HEARD ME/ONC/A\nCOWARD WOULD HIT A y\nWOMAN! WHY DONTy\nYOuHIT R\u2014e\nAMAN?.rg\nITIUC\n1\nBY AL SWTS\nWELL; ANYWAYS.\nMUTT, THAT PROVES\nYOUREAMAN!\u2014\nK\n7%\n623\nAL\nSwntl\nt\nA\nf","height":"26772","width":"19576"}}
